public class Button
extends com.google.gwt.user.client.ui.FocusPanel
implements com.google.gwt.user.client.ui.HasHTML

A push-button widget build with div elements using only CSS to create shading effects. Uses the same interface as Button (Except for the wrap method). The button is based on the technique used in several Google™ applications and described on the web site stopdesign.com.

Difference with HTML button element

While this widget tries to act as much as a button there are still difference between this widget and a HTML button element as used in the gwt Button widget.

  1. Access Key: This widget doesn't support the accessKey attribute. This attribute is only supported on input elements and can't be added to other elements.
  2. HTML form support: A button element has a type attribute. When this attribute has the value submit or reset they get specific functionality that operates on a HTML form element. This widget doesn't support such functionality. To get the similar behavior a ClickListener could be used.

CSS Style Rules

  • .cbg-Button { }
  • .cbg-ButtonOuter { }
  • .cbg-ButtonInner { }
  • .cbg-ButtonTop { }
  • .cbg-ButtonContent { }
  • .cbg-Button-active { }
  • .cbg-Button-disabled { }
  • .cbg-Button-focus { }
  • .cbg-Button-hover { }

See Also:
http://stopdesign.com/archive/2009/02/04/recreating-the-button.html

setColor

public void setColor(int hue,
                     int saturation)
Sets the color of the Button using hue and saturation. The specific effect of shading is created using a fixed set of brightness parameters to calculate the RGB values from hue, saturation and brightness.

The text color is based on the saturation level. If it's higher then 50 the text color will be white, otherwise it will be black. The color for the text of a disabled button is similarly created, but also uses the hue. If the calculated text colors need to be different they can be overridden with the method setColorText(String, String).

Parameters:
hue - the hue component of the color, between 0-359
saturation - the saturation component of the color, between 0-100

setColorText

public void setColorText(java.lang.String colorText,
                         java.lang.String colorDisabled)
Set the color of the font and the color of the font when the button is disabled. This method can be used to set an alternative font color, in case the default font color's are not as desired. The default font color is black and default disabled font color is #888888. When a custom color is set via setColor(int, int) the font color is white and the disabled color will depend on the hue and saturation used.

Parameters:
colorText - Color of the text
colorDisabled - Color of the text when the button is disabled

setSize

public void setSize(int precentage)
Sets the size of the font, implicitly sets the size of the button, because the button scales accordingly. The default size is 70% of the derived font size of the button. In practice this means the button is sized relatively to the general font size used.

Parameters:
precentage - Size of font in percentage.

setSizeRatio

public void setSizeRatio(double ratio,
                         int padding)
Sets the ratio between the button size and the font size. The ratio is applied to the height of elements and the calculated ratio's are set in em on the elements. The padding is applied to the left and right padding of the div containing the text and is specified in px.

Parameters:
ratio - Ratio between button size and font size
padding - Padding left and right side of text in px

onHover

protected void onHover(boolean hover)
Set the button in hover state if hover is true, but only if the button doesn't have focus, in that case the focus style applied overrides the hover style. If hover state is enabled the button the CSS class name cbg-hover is applied.

Parameters:
hover - Set button in hover state if true
